05001nam a22006615i 9780824845759DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248457597 a10.1515/97808248457592doi  a(DE-B1597)483913  a(OCoLC)1013946132  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0100002bisacsh1 aWiegele, Katharine L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvesting in Miracles :bEl Shaddai and the Transformation of Popular Catholicism in the Philippines /cKatharine L. Wiegele. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Seeking El Shaddai -- tChapter 2. Golden Rules, Miracle Investments, and the Seed-Faith Principle -- tChapter 3. Mass Media and Religious Experience -- tChapter 4. Urban Spaces of Community and Congregation -- tChapter 5. Stories of Transformation and Desire -- tChapter 6. Local Religious Life -- tChapter 7. Spiritual Warfare in Sinag and Bandong -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the early 1980s, approximately ten million people have turned to charismatic businessman-turned-preacher "Brother Mike" and his Catholic "prosperity" movement, El Shaddai DWXI Prayer Partners Foundation International, Inc. Investing in Miracles offers an in-depth look at this unique indigenous movement, characterized by its effective use of mass media and its huge, emotion-filled outdoor rallies. The book investigates the sociocultural, political, and economic contexts of El Shaddai's popularity among the Filipino urban poor and aspiring middle classes and explores its significance for its followers, which reaches well beyond promises of appliances, salary raises, jobs abroad, and healing. Katharine Wiegele argues that Shaddai's theology directly engages and affirms desires for the material signs of modernity in ways that the mainstream Philippine Roman Catholic Church and Filipino leftist movements do not. At stake for its many adherents are their place and identity within the broader society; the meaning of their experiences of poverty, suffering, and oppression; and the relevance of their very notions of God, Christian community, and Christian life.Wiegele evocatively captures the religious and everyday experiences of her informants' lives in poor squatter neighborhoods of Manila. She is particularly sensitive to El Shaddai's delicate and often contorted relationship with the Catholic Church, which accepts the movement reluctantly, fearful of losing the loyalty of millions of faithful Catholics. While anchored in the local realities of the Philippines, Investing in Miracles will be of great interest to readers elsewhere for its exploration of religious seduction and interpretation, the interface between religion and politics, and the relevance of religion for the urban disenfranchised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484575940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824845759423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824845759/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (200